	<text>
		<body>
			<div type="entry">
				<pb facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary50.jpg"/>
				<dateline><date when="1862-03-24">Monday 25.</date></dateline>
				<p><note>This is mis-dated. March 25th was a Tuesday in 1862. It appears that Linn
						miscalculated and that this should have been Monday March 24th.</note>I went
					to the <objectName type="ship">Jenny </objectName>— the <objectName type="ship"
						>Curlew</objectName> runs over every fifteen minutes, just where the bridge
					was burned. I was one minute too late. Just then<persName key="George Shorkley"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper002"
						> Lt. Shorkley</persName> and <persName key="Lt. Gaulen"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper149"
						>Lt. Gaulen</persName> came up in a <objectName type="vehicle"
						>boat</objectName>, and as they told me there was nothing to be done in
					camp, and as my luxurious quarters last night gave me a cold, I concluded to
					stay. I acted as guide, and took them to see what remained of <persName>Gov.
						Lyon’s</persName> palace, the <placeName>cemetery</placeName>, and the car
					house. Then we went into a French bootmaker’s. <persName key="Lt. Gaulen"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper149"
						>Gaulen </persName>talked to him in his own tongue. Met <persName
						key="John Morris"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper057"
						>Morris</persName>, who took us around to Gen. Reno’s quarters — a white
					house, nicely furnished. While here, a chaplain told us a romantic story of
						<persName key="Dr. Cutter"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper124"
						>Dr. Cutter</persName>’s daughter, the brigade surgeon of the 2nd Brigade,
					who died this morning here of what they call the Roanoke fever. She had
					requested to be taken to <placeName key="Roanoke Island"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl076"
						>Roanoke Island</placeName> and buried beside a young man by the name of
						<persName>Plummer</persName>, whose real name was <persName>Lidd</persName>,
					and who was with <persName key="John Brown"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_personography.xml#jmlper052"
						>John Brown</persName> in <placeName key="Virginia"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl089"
						>Virginia</placeName>, and who had been attacked by some disease of the
						stomach.<pb
						facs="https://leaf.bucknell.edu/sites/default/files/2026-01/diary51.jpg"
					/>the night before. The battle of Roanoke, and died the same night. We went from
					there and dined at the <placeName key="Gaston House"
						ref="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/BucknellDSC/jmlinn/refs/heads/main/jmlinn_gazetteer.xml#linnpl112"
						>Gaston House</placeName>. <objectName type="food">Corn bread</objectName>,
						<objectName type="food">rice soup</objectName>, <objectName>roasted Irish
						potatoes</objectName>, and <objectName type="food">rice pudding</objectName>
					was all [we had?] at the first-class hotel. [And?] a morsel of <objectName
						type="food">wheat bread</objectName>.</p>
			</div>
		</body>
	</text>
